{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015iCcdASfdwXs7WqeETSUCj","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# TASK — Calculation note: TRISO particle failure under accident heating\n2\t\n3\tYou are an engineer. `inputs/` describes TRISO-coated fuel particles (a UO₂ kernel inside\n4\tbuffer / inner-PyC / SiC / outer-PyC layers), the fuel elements that contain them (spheres of\n5\t16,400 particles; compacts of ~1,600), the irradiation each element experienced, and the\n6\taccident-heating schedule each was then subjected to in a furnace. A material-property annex is\n7\tprovided — it is deliberately complete.\n8\t\n9\tFor each heating case in `inputs/02_cases.md`, predict — with your reasoning, assumptions, and\n10\ta confidence level per number:\n11\t1. how many particles fail during the heating (out of the element's population), and when\n12\t   (onset time, or which phase of a staged schedule);\n13\t2. the final fractional release of Kr-85 and Cs-137 from the element;\n14\t3. the ranking: which case suffers most and why (temperature and burnup sensitivities).\n15\t\n16\tState which assumption is most uncertain. Work fully offline — build from physics and the given\n17\tinputs only; do not look up these experiments' published results. Cite the correlations you use.\n18\tPut the calculation note (output/calculation_note.md) and all working files in output/.\n19\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bee5a296-41c8-4882-8791-56b3c65b42f4","uuid":"0cf40bed-3cde-4b99-b8e0-0a3a882714ab","timestamp":"2026-07-03T16:57:59.284Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/bench/triso_fableV/TASK.md","content":"# TASK — Calculation note: TRISO particle failure under accident heating\n\nYou are an engineer. `inputs/` describes TRISO-coated fuel particles (a UO₂ kernel inside\nbuffer / inner-PyC / SiC / outer-PyC layers), the fuel elements that contain them (spheres of\n16,400 particles; compacts of ~1,600), the irradiation each element experienced, and the\naccident-heating schedule each was then subjected to in a furnace. A material-property annex is\nprovided — it is deliberately complete.\n\nFor each heating case in `inputs/02_cases.md`, predict — with your reasoning, assumptions, and\na confidence level per number:\n1. how many particles fail during the heating (out of the element's population), and when\n   (onset time, or which phase of a staged schedule);\n2. the final fractional release of Kr-85 and Cs-137 from the element;\n3. the ranking: which case suffers most and why (temperature and burnup sensitivities).\n\nState which assumption is most uncertain. Work fully offline — build from physics and the given\ninputs only; do not look up these experiments' published results. Cite the correlations you use.\nPut the calculation note (output/calculation_note.md) and all working files in output/.\n","numLines":19,"startLine":1,"totalLines":19}}}
