{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-fable-5","id":"msg_01FydkNHX6Kyiv3ngRWB21Ur","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Done. `output/calculation_note.md` is complete, backed by a working model (`output/model.py`, raw run log in `model_output.txt`), built entirely from the property annex and physics — no external lookups.\n\n**How I modeled it:** two release channels. (1) Pressure-vessel failure: fission gas (0.30 Xe+Kr per fission) plus CO builds pressure in the buffer void, loading the SiC shell; failure probability from the annex Weibull statistics (873 MPa, m = 8.02), tracked phase-by-phase along each furnace schedule. (2) Cs-137 diffusion through *intact* SiC: a finite-difference solve of the 36 µm shell using the Eq 10.9 coefficient, including the irradiation phase first so the SiC enters the furnace pre-loaded. Kr-85 is retained by intact SiC, so it only escapes from failed particles (Eqs 10.7–10.8) and is compared to the annex's one-particle detection thresholds.\n\n**Headline predictions:**\n\n| Case | Failed particles | Onset | Kr-85 release | Cs-137 release |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| A1 (1600 °C/500 h) | 0 (E[N]=0.0006) | — (1600 °C hold if any) | < 6×10⁻⁵ | ≈ 3×10⁻² |\n| A2 (1800 °C/100 h) | 0, upside 0–2 | 2nd 1800 °C hold | < 6×10⁻⁵ | ≈ 4×10⁻⁴ |\n| B (staged →1800 °C/400 h) | 0, upside 0–5 | phases 3–4 (1800 °C) | < 7×10⁻⁵ | ≈ 1.2×10⁻¹ |\n| C1 (1600 °C/304 h, 13.9 %) | 0 (E[N]=0.007) | late 1600 °C hold | < 6×10⁻⁴ | ≈ 1×10⁻² |\n| C2 (1600 °C/304 h, 11.1 %) | 0 (E[N]=0.0009) | none | < 6×10⁻⁴ | ≈ 2×10⁻³ |\n\nPeak SiC stresses (104–186 MPa) never approach the 873 MPa strength, so with m = 8 the pressure route gives essentially zero failures everywhere — robust even doubling the pressure. The interesting physics is in Cs: the SiC breakthrough lag time (~590 h at 1600 °C, ~270 h at 1800 °C) relative to each hold ordains the ranking **B ≫ C1 > A2 > A1 > C2** — case B is fully broken through (400 h at 1800 °C on top of a 15,216 h/1140 °C irradiation that pre-loaded the shell), while A2, despite being hottest, is held too briefly to leak much Cs. Burnup sensitivity shows up as P_fail ∝ burnup⁸ in the C1/C2 pair (~7× ratio).\n\nThe most uncertain assumption, stated in the note: the Cs boundary condition at the SiC inner face (concentration continuity, no solubility partition) — it biases the absolute Cs numbers high by up to 1–2 orders of magnitude, though not the ranking. For failure counts the key caveat is the absence of any SiC corrosion/decomposition kinetics in the annex, which is why the 1800 °C cases carry explicit upside ranges."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":355,"cache_read_input_tokens":101478,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":355},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bee5a296-41c8-4882-8791-56b3c65b42f4","uuid":"096942fe-73fb-455f-b7e3-0a38e966dfa2","request_id":"req_011CcfVkcmd5VLmfxPVshSAC"}
